How To Start TermTA

Syntax:  TTA DatabaseName Switch

Where "DatabaseName" is a name you have chosen for this database. You must
supply a name. If you don't enter it on the command line, then TERMTA will
ask you for one before it will run. The purpose of the "DatabaseName" is
for those who play in more then one game of TA and thus may have different
characters with different configurations. I usually call my database the
same name as the BBS the game is on. Easy to remember then, which database
goes to which game of TeleArena.

Where "Switch" can be any letter or number. "Switch" is OPTIONAL, but if
used, MUST follow the "DatabaseName". The purpose of "Switch" is to bypass
TERMTA's prompt that asks if you want to dial a BBS. Sometimes you may
already be online when you want to start TERMTA. In those cases you won't
need to dial and log onto a BBS. Thus you don't need to be bothered by
TERMTA's prompt asking if you want to dial in. Just enter any character
here. If character found, prompt is bypassed.

There are 3 ways to use TERMTA:

1) Offline. TERMTA can be run offline for various things.
  
2) You can use TERMTA to connect to a BBS.

3) You can start TERMTA after you have already connected to the BBS
   using your comm program.

   If you need to use your comm program for logging onto the BBS (in case
   you want/need to do other things on-line like file transfers, etc..)

   You can always Exit/Shell from your comm program (make sure not to drop
   carrier) and then start TERMTA.

   Just make sure to answer NO when asked if you want to dial a BBS
   (no need to dial since you are already online) or use the optional
   "Switch" parameter on the command line to bypass this step.

   When using this method, make sure your comm program connects to the BBS
   at the same settings you have configured in TERMTA. Simply go to TERMTA's
   F8 menu (do this offline). Jot down the modem settings (baud, port,
   handshaking, etc), and set your comm program to use the same settings.

   Then call your BBS with your comm program. Do your e-mail, file transfers,
   etc.. When ready to play TA, exit your comm without dropping carrier
   (if you are shelling, you should set your comm program to swap itself to
   XMS/EMS), start TERMTA. Play TA.

   When done playing you can log off the BBS while in TERMTA, or exit
   TERMTA and return to your comm program.

   If you decide that after playing TA, you need to get back in your comm
   program, you can do so without having to redial the BBS. Simply exit
   TERMTA and start your comm program WITHOUT sending the modem init string.
   In Telemate, you would use the /O switch to do this.

   FINAL NOTES:
   If you shell to DOS to run TERMTA, or use a hotkey, you'll probably wise
   to configure your comm program to shell itself to EMS/XMS/DISK.

   With this method, I recommend starting TERMTA while you are at your
   BBS's main menu prompt. Make sure if you get a lot of global messages,
   that they are turned off first before starting TERMTA

