How to use features with Mouse or Keyboard

Previously I explained how to start TERMTA and how to correct any problems
when running it. So this section will focus on how to use the Mouse or
Keyboard to move around in TERMTA.

When using the keyboard, the following keys run the following features:
You can use the mouse to click on these also.
   
   F1   Macros                CTRL-C   Open/Close a capture file
   F2   Config Menu           CTRL-D   Shell to DOS
   F3   View Maps             CTRL-G   Group Health Display
   F4   Display Exits         CTRL-E   Your Health Display
   F5   Auto Share            CTRL-T   List Exits
   F6   Auto Roam             CTRL-F   List Items For Sale
   F7   Auto Restore          CTRL-S   List your Stats
   F8   Auto Reroll           CTRL-K   List your Spells
   F9   Auto Attack           CTRL-B   Scrollback buffer
   F10  Auto Heal             CTRL-L   Look
                              CTRL-A   Dial BBS
                              CTRL-I   List your Inventory
                              CTRL-X   Display your Experience points

Besides the above, TERMTA comes with a script language for making macros.
These Macros can be found on the Macro Screen (F7). TERMTA assigns each
macro to a letter. These macros can be run by using the ALT key and the
letter for that macro.

To use a mouse to run the ALT key macros, simply click on the letter
at the TOP of the TERMTA screen.

                         MOVEMENT KEYS 

As you know TA requires you to type in NW, NE, etc to move around.
This can be slow and tiring (not to mention boring). TERMTA
alleviates this problem by allowing you other choices for moving.

Mouse:  Use the left mouse button to click on the on-screen compass, or
        up/down buttons

Keypad: Use the numeric keypad (make sure Num Lock is off) for moving.

                                N
                         [ 7 ][ 8 ][ 9 ]
                       W [ 4 ]     [ 6 ] E
                         [ 1 ][ 2 ][ 3 ]
                         [ 0 ][ . ]
                          Up  Down

Of course, you can still type in the commands manually at the command line
should you so desire.

